As the Dodgers often do, they bounced Stripling between the rotation and bullpen throughout 2019, which is why it was so frustrating to his prospective fantasy managers to see his reported trade to the Angels quashed in February. While his 2019 wasn't as sparkling as his 2018, it contained similarly appealing peripherals: 3.47 FIP (five-hundredths off his 2018 number), 5.4% walk rate, 50% ground ball rate, 8.5 Runs Above Average with his curveball. #FreeStripling might again be a popular hash tag in 2020, as a committed rotation spot might go a long way towards cementing him a top-50 fantasy starter. For now, throw a dart.

After throwing just 12 minor league innings rehabbing from Tommy John surgery in 2018, Pineda turned in a solid 2019 campaign, albeit truncated with a 60-game suspension for testing positive for a banned diuretic. As one might expect after such a long layoff, Pineda improved as the season progressed. His first half ERA and WHIP were 4.56 and 1.18, compared to 3.04 and 1.13 after. Pineda's K% improved from 22% to 26.7%. Minnesota non-tendered the 31-year-old righthander but quickly signed him to a two-year contract. Pineda will return to the Twins' rotation after missing the remaining 39 games on his suspension. If he can maintain his strikeout gains, Pineda's low WHIP and potential for wins render him a mid-tier fantasy starter.

Injuries ruined Betances' 2019, beginning with a shoulder problem that cost him five months, and concluding with a season-ending Achilles' injury that occurred in his only appearance all year. He's expected to be healthy to begin 2020, and should occupy a late-inning role for his new team across town, the Mets surely regarding him a fallback option should closer Edwin Diaz struggle for the second straight year. Before the injuries, Betances was riding a record five-straight seasons of at least 100 strikeouts in relief, so there's reason to believe he can contribute to fantasy teams even in a setup role. Select him for holds, Ks and the ERA/WHIP help, with those most valuable in leagues with daily transactions.

Despite losing 14 games last season, Alcantara gave the Marlins plenty to be excited about, as he pitched 197.1 innings, earned an All-Star berth and flashed his vast potential at various points in the campaign. The right-hander is armed with a mid-to-upper-90s fastball that occasionally touches triple digits and possesses late movement. However, it would be a stretch to say that Alcantara has put it all together, as his secondary offerings remain works in progress, limiting his ability to keep hitters off balance and thus generate strikeouts. It's fair to want better than Alcantara's 18.0 K%, given his ability to throw heat, though that number did jump to 20.0% over the second half of the campaign. Further improvement is dependent on Alcantara's continued growth in terms of both consistency and command. He's far from a true ace but may head up the Marlins' staff in 2020.

Universally regarded one of the top starting pitching prospects in baseball entering 2019, May parlayed a 3.38 ERA, 1.13 WHIP and 24.6% strikeout rate in 20 starts between Double-A Tulsa and Triple-A Oklahoma City into initially a big-league rotation spot and ultimately a swingman role, during which he had a sparkling 6.4 K-to-walk ratio. He's an imposing pitcher with a high-90s sinker, which with his size has helped him generate many grounders throughout his professional career and makes him a low-risk pick, even with as little experience as he has. May should be in the mix for a Dodgers rotation spot, but even if he remains in a swingman role, can contribute enough to warrant late-round mixed league consideration. It's also perhaps your last chance to secure him on the cheap in dynasty leagues.

Kela's rocky 2019 campaign included two trips to the injured list (both for elbow inflammation) and two suspensions (one for violating team rules and one for throwing at an opponent's head). In his 29.2 healthy innings he found a good deal of success, finishing with a 2.12 ERA and 1.01 WHIP. It took a .225 BABIP and an 89.6% strand rate to get him there, however, and his 3.52 FIP and 4.28 xFIP tell a considerably less impressive story. His 27.7 K% and 9.2 BB% aren't close to elite closer material. He probably won't have to be anywhere near elite to keep the closing job all season for a Pirates team that lacks quality alternatives. Still, injury worries and character concerns affect his job security, limiting him to the lower tier of closing options this draft season.

The Braves were hopeful entering the 2019 campaign as Gausman pitched well after being acquired from the Orioles in July 2018. Unfortunately, the success was fleeting as Gausman was released in early August after posting a gaudy 6.19 ERA in 16 starts. The Reds claimed the right-hander and inserted him into their bullpen where Gausman thrived despite a 4.07 ERA, sporting a 1.16 WHIP with 29 strikeouts in 22 1/3 innings, walking just five. The Giants signed Gausman after the Reds let him go following the season. The plan is for Gausman to return to starting, hoping the pitcher-friendly dimensions of Oracle Park spur a career rejuvenation. There's reason for optimism as homers have always been an issue for Gausman -- see his career 13.5% HR/FB mark. If Gausman fails as a starter, he's proven capable of transitioning back to a reliever.

Oberg appeared to be the presumptive favorite to close for the Rockies this season after posting a 2.25 ERA in 56 innings in 2019. He moved into that role in the second half of last year, picking up five saves before being shut down due to blood clots. Manager Bud Black elected to go with experience over performance, however, naming veteran Wade Davis his closer at the start of camp despite Davis' miserable 8.65 ERA last season. Given how much better Oberg pitched in 2019, it's easy to see him reclaiming the job fairly early in the year, placing him near the top of the list of non-closing relief targets. That's not to say he'd be an elite closer if given the position. His career-best 26.0 K% last season hardly jumps off the page, and he still calls Coors Field home.

After a four-year stretch of mostly tepid numbers out of the bullpen, Hudson revived his career last season, first with Toronto and later with Washington. Collectively, his 2.47 ERA was more than a full run better than any mark he had previously posted as a reliever. Even better, that ERA shrunk to 1.44 over 25 innings with Washington, the team he will pitch for again in 2020. Nonetheless, there are reasons to be cautious about overhyping Hudson's performance, as his 5.08 xFIP hints at likely regression. The right-hander is unlikely to see a repeat of his .247 BABIP or 81.8 LOB%, as both numbers fall far outside his career norm. Furthermore, Hudson's strikeout rate was an unimpressive 23.4% despite a fastball that clocked in at more than 96 mph. Hudson is likely to fall behind Sean Doolittle in the bullpen pecking order anyway, limiting his fantasy value to leagues that count holds.

Forgive him his so-so pitching stat line from his 2019 debut season, as McKay breezed through three competitive levels while continuing to deal with a lack of clarity with his role on the hitting side. He thoroughly dominated the Double- and Triple-A levels, posting a combined 1.10 ERA and 36.7% strikeout rate in 13 starts and two relief appearances, and in three of his 11 big-league starts despite frequently riding the Triple-A shuttle he posted Bill James Game Scores of 66 or greater. McKay's long-term ceiling is high and he should factor into the Rays' 2020 plans, more so on the pitching than hitting side, though he's a dual-eligible you can use in the latter if he factors into the DH or first base mix on certain days. He's a worthy late-round stash.

Cease, one of the top pitching prospects in the game entering last season, reached the majors in July despite what was a 4.48 ERA in 15 season-opening start at Triple-A Charlotte, not to mention a career 11.4% walk rate in the minors. Those control issues revealed themselves in the majors as well; he had only three quality starts and the fifth-worst walk rate (10.7%) of any pitcher who made at least 10 starts from the date of his July 3 debut forward. Cease will need to address that if he's to break through in 2020, but he does have electric stuff once he clears those hurdles. He's an AL-only flier, and more of a dynasty-league prospect than a redraft target.

After debuting as a reliever in 2018, Hudson earned a spot in the Cardinals' Opening Day rotation last season and held onto it the rest of the way. His 3.35 ERA suggests he acquitted himself very well, but the rest of his stat line tells a very different story. The 1.58-run gap between his ERA and his 4.93 FIP was more than half a run larger than any other qualified starter, leaving the door open for a precipitous fall this season. The Cardinals are a strong defensive team, and a pitcher with Hudson's high 56.9% groundball rate is well-positioned to take advantage of that defense, but defense can't reliably cover for the faults of a pitcher with an 18.0 K% and a 11.4 BB%. Expect a more mediocre ERA to go with Hudson's low strikeout total this season.

Bassitt bounced between the minors and majors from 2014-18 before settling in as a full-time member of Oakland's starting staff last season. The right-hander made 25 starts, posting a 3.95 ERA (4.51 FIP) and a .234 BAA. For the first time in his career, he was an above-average strikeout pitcher, as his 23.0 K% was nearly three ticks higher than his 2018 mark. The improvement was partly due to a gain in his fastball velocity, which averaged 93.5 mph last season. He also did well limiting hard contact, holding opposing batters to an 87 mph average exit velocity. In what may have been a precursor to his 2020 role, Bassitt logged five scoreless innings out of the bullpen near the end of the campaign, striking out nine. Pitching in relief would help solidify Bassitt's place in the majors but would put a significant dent in his fantasy value.

Signed by the bullpen-starved Marlins during the offseason, Kintzler might be the odds-on-favorite to end up as their Opening Day closer, in large part because of his �experience� in the role (45 saves for the 2016-17 Twins). His skill set isn't that of a dominant finisher, but his ground-ball leaning and good control represent a somewhat low-risk option, supporting his case as an NL-only target if you're going the cheap route for saves.

Houser generated little buzz in fantasy circles heading into last season, but that isn't the case this time around. Houser mainly pitched in the minors and in relief over the first half of the season, but he spent the final three months in the rotation, and when it was all said and done, he was one of the Brewers' best pitchers in 2019. He was particularly good to close out the campaign, posting a 3.02 ERA, 1.03 WHIP and 9.8 K/9 over his last 10 starts. Houser mainly relies on a mid-90s fastball and his curveball, but also mixes in a slider and changeup, so he has enough options to keep hitters guessing. With the way he finished last season, he heads into the 2020 campaign with a firm grasp on a spot somewhere near the top or in the middle of the Brewers' starting rotation.

Cueto returned to the majors just one year and 39 days removed from August 2018 Tommy John surgery to post a pair of encouraging initial September outings followed by a pair of stinkers. Small sample, yes, but combining those with his six minor league rehabilitation starts, he had 34 K's compared to 10 walks, which at least offers some promise entering 2020. Now 34, Cueto is almost assured a rotation spot with the Giants for so long as he's healthy -- a $21-plus-million salary will do that for you -- and if he's looking good during spring training, he'd be worth a deep-mixed or NL-only mid-to-late round pick based upon his past track record.

Tommy John surgery in June 2018 cost Montgomery most of the past two seasons, and the four-game sample he offered between the minors and majors last year offered little information. Before the operation, he had posted good (yet hardly elite) numbers as a member of the Yankees rotation, leaning more to the matchups side in fantasy leagues as indicated by his 3.61 ERA against sub-.500 teams in his career to date. Montgomery will be an important pitcher to watch in Grapefruit League play, especially as he competes for a rotation spot following James Paxton's injury. If he can stick with the team, he'd warrant an AL-only late-round speculative pick.

Pomeranz, once a promising starter, is on the cusp of carving out a second career as a dominant reliever. He began the season with the Giants, posting a 5.68 ERA and 1.61, starting the majority of the time. San Francisco dealt Pomeranz to the Brewers at the trade deadline. Perhaps encouraged by Pomeranz ending his Giants tenure with 5.1 innings of scoreless relief, along with their own conversion of Josh Hader to the bullpen, Milwaukee used Pomeranz as a reliever, and he registered a sparkling 2.39 ERA and .91 WHIP with 45 whiffs in 26.1 innings. The southpaw signed with the Padres, an organization known for getting the most out of their bullpen. Pomeranz is one of the top options in leagues scoring holds and can help support ratios and add strikeouts in standard leagues.

Knebel succumbed to Tommy John surgery shortly before the start of the 2019 season, putting his anticipated return timetable somewhere in the range of May. Once healthy, he could quickly move into the Brewers' late-inning mix thanks to his pre-surgery combination of near-40% strikeout and near-50% ground-ball rates. A closer job might be a tough ask in 2020, but Knebel might emerge as one of the better holds/strikeouts relief options by the season's second half -- if his recovery goes smoothly.

Drafted in the second round in 2017, Canning was fast-tracked, culminating in an April promotion after just three starts with Triple-A Salt Lake to begin the 2019 campaign. The 23-year old held his own in his freshman year before being shut down in mid-August with elbow inflammation. Prior, Canning tossed 90.1 innings and fanned an impressive 96 batters. The right-hander features a four-pitch arsenal including a 93-mph fastball, curveball, slider and changeup. However, he had only a five-mph delta between his heater and changeup, limiting the effectiveness of each. Canning's best strikeout pitch is his slider, which generated a 22.3% swinging strike rate last season. The Angels fortified their staff in the offseason, but Canning is still expected to fill a mid-rotation role. He was throwing in November, so the elbow issue cutting short his rookie season was minor and won't affect his availability for spring training.

Castillo pitched wherever the Rays needed him to last season, opening six games and finishing second on the team with eight saves. Last year's save leader, Emilio Pagan, was shipped to San Diego, potentially opening up more ninth-inning opportunities for Castillo, even though his numbers can't compare with Nick Anderson's eye-popping stats. Then again, this is the Rays we're talking about, so creative pitcher usage is to be expected. Castillo's numbers don't match the game's truly elite relievers, but he's still a legitimate late-inning weapon. In 125.1 career innings, he has posted a 3.30 ERA, a 28.5 K% and a 8.6 BB%. In leagues deep enough to roster a handful of non-closing relievers, Castillo is a prime target, as whatever saves he manages can be taken as a bonus. He's not quite good enough for shallower formats, though, unless he's regularly closing games.

Rockies closers don't age gracefully, with Davis the latest victim. After surviving the 2018 campaign, posting 43 saves despite a 4.13 ERA, things fell apart for Davis last season. At the end of July, Davis was sitting on a 6.82 ERA and 1.74 WHIP when he was replaced as closer by Scott Oberg. When Oberg's season was cut short in mid-August, Davis got another crack at the job, but it was short-lived after a blown save. He finished the season in low-leverage scenarios, where he's likely to remain for the 2020 season. Davis' strikeout rate was its lowest since 2013 when he was a starter for the Royals, and his walk rate was a career worst. Now 34-years old, there's little hope of a turnaround.

For the second straight season, Voth served as a �sixth starter� of sorts with the Nationals, ultimately completing 2019 a regular member of their rotation with a 2.61 ERA in four September starts. He showed improvement with both his four-seam fastball and curveball in the process, things that could put him in better position to claim the team's open fifth-starter job this spring. Any Grapefruit League success could thrust him into the late-round NL-only discussion, so monitor his progress.

Purchased from the Twins by the Mariners in July, Magill was thrust into their late-inning mix, although much of the reason was the dearth of quality alternatives due to injuries. He posted a surprisingly effective stat line. In 19 August/September appearances, he had a 3.00 ERA, a 1.11 WHIP and a 29.9% strikeout rate, even going 5-for-6 converting save chances in his month-long stint in the role. Magill enters 2020 as the favorite for ninth-inning duties, and the tweaks he made while with the Mariners make him worth a late-round pick if you end up waiting on saves.

Porcello's ERAs since his Cy Young campaign in 2016: 4.65, 4.28, 5.52. The ERA estimators say Porcello deserved better in his final season in Boston, but not much better. His walk rate held steady at 5.9%, but his strikeout rate fell five percentage points to 18.6%. His home-run rate shot back up to 1.6, right around where it was in the first modern juiced-ball year of 2017. While Porcello had a 21.3 K-BB% in September, he still got knocked around, and aside from spin rate, there's little in his seasonal numbers to hang your hat on. At least Porcello remains durable, clearing 170 innings in 11 straight seasons. There is value in that volume in certain points-based formats. Porcello signed a one-year deal with the Mets over the offseason, and those looking to preserve their ratios in rotisserie leagues will want to steer clear, or at least stream Porcello carefully early on.

Means quickly became the ace of the Orioles' staff during his rookie campaign. He was the team's lone representative in the All-Star Game and finished second in American League Rookie of the Year voting. The southpaw racked up 12 wins on the season -- more than 20% of the team's total -- while posting a 3.60 ERA. Advanced metrics were not as encouraging, as Means' 5.48 xFIP exceeded his ERA by nearly two runs, thanks largely to a massive 50% fly ball rate and a poor 19.0 K%. Still, Means did many things well, including limiting hard contact -- per FanGraphs, the 27.5 Hard% opponents registered against him was the top mark in the league (minimum 150 innings) -- and notching a stellar 6.0 BB%. That softens the harsh xFIP considerably, though Means isn't very appealing as a fantasy target due to his low strikeout numbers and frequent tough matchups in a loaded division.

Last season represented a sizable step backward for Happ. Like many others, Happ saw his home run rate spike in 2019, from 1.37 HR in 2018 to 1.9. The baseball itself isn't the only thing to blame. Happ's Zone% fell to a career-low 38.8%, and his strikeout rate plummeted six percentage points. The left-hander battled biceps tendinitis late in the season and played a minimal role for New York in the postseason, throwing just 3.2 innings across three appearances (zero starts). Now 37, Happ faces a somewhat uncertain future -- there were rumors that the Yankees were looking to trade him during the offseason. He would likely have more security in a starting role elsewhere. With the Yankees, Happ will have a short leash in the rotation. Happ may be best suited for bulk relief duty at this stage, given his third-time-through-the-batting-order numbers in recent seasons.

Barnes is a very good major-league reliever who could be great if he ever fixes his control woes. Blessed with a fastball that sits 96-97 mph and a hard curveball which he used as his primary pitch last season (50.7% usage), Barnes was able to strike out batters at a career-high 38.6% clip in 2019, ranking sixth among qualified relievers. He managed that lofty strikeout rate despite one of the 10 worst Zone% among that same group (35.9%). With all of those balls landing outside the strike zone, Barnes' already-unsightly walk rate ticked up to 13.3%. He got a save in his first appearance of the season but was passed over for the full-time closing job in favor of Ryan Brasier, and later on, Brandon Workman. Alex Cora is gone, but interim manager Ron Roenicke has already said he's sticking by Workman to begin the year, leaving Barnes for the list of possible speculative stashes on draft day.

Plesac, the nephew of former big-league closer Dan Plesac, posted a 1.71 ERA in 10 starts between Double- and Triple-A to begin last season, earning himself a late-May promotion to the Indians, whose rotation was plagued by injuries at the time. He turned in four quality starts in his first six tries, locking down a permanent spot, holding his own over 21 total big-league turns. Plesac should hold that spot into 2020, but his underlying metrics raise concerns: 4.94 FIP, .255 BABIP, 39% ground ball rate, 39% hard contact rate allowed. Consider him more of a matchups type -- he had a 3.03 ERA in his 13 turns against sub-.500 teams -- rather than a locked-in member of a mixed league roster.

Mahle will begin spring training on the outside looking in at the Reds' rotation battle, but as a sneakily skilled sixth starter, he should squeak his way into value at some point in 2020. Despite awful 2019 results, he improved his walk rate significantly, slashing it to 5.4% in his eight second-half starts in fact, and boosted his average fastball velocity slightly, offering further promise. Mahle would have to open eyes during spring training to be more than a bench stash, but for the time being he's a wise one to make in NL-only leagues.

Through his first eight starts of 2019, Sanchez was 0-6 with a 5.27 ERA. He went on to go 11-2 with a 3.38 ERA over his final 22 regular-season starts, with a 2.50 ERA in 18 postseason innings for the World Series champs. Sanchez has enjoyed an unlikely career renaissance over the past couple years since making the cut fastball a bigger part of his arsenal. He still does not miss many bats (18.8 K% last season), but Sanchez has done a better job of inducing soft, playable contact for the defense behind him. In fact, Sanchez ranked among the top 15% of the league (to the good side) in average exit velocity and hard-hit rate allowed, per Statcast. Now entering the final guaranteed year of his deal with Washington, Sanchez will be back to anchor the No. 4 spot in the rotation and should be viewed as a viable, if unexciting, staff filler in fantasy leagues.

Gibson's rough 2019 campaign began with an E. coli infection and ended with a demotion to the bullpen. In between, he also battled ulcerative colitis and saw his ERA rise to 4.84 -- more than a run higher than the 3.62 mark he posted in 2018. That Gibson hurled 160 innings despite dealing with illness is admirable in itself and likely explains the right-hander's second-half struggles (5.92 ERA, .307 BAA). Not all went south for Gibson last season, however, as his 3.80 xFIP was a career best. He also continued to evolve as a strikeout pitcher, registering a 22.7 K% and 13.1% swinging-strike rate -- both career highs. That bodes well for a bounceback 2020 campaign if Gibson is able to manage his ulcerative colitis and adjust to his new ballpark in Texas. Consider him a streaming option in mixed fantasy leagues.

Contrary to recent trends, Fiers has been a better pitcher since parting ways with Houston following the 2017 campaign. He took over as the ace of Oakland's staff last season and compiled a sterling 15-4 record that included the second no-hitter of his career. However, it's rarely wise to get worked up over a pitcher's win percentage, and that certainly holds true for Fiers, as he posted a career-worst 5.19 xFIP last season due largely to an elevated fly ball rate (38.8%) and paltry 16.7 K% (fourth lowest among qualified starters). The luck factor was almost certainly in play for the right-hander in 2019, as he registered an abnormally low .254 BABIP and a surprisingly high (considering his lack of swing-and-miss stuff) 78.5 LOB%. Pitching in Oakland softens some of Fiers' risk factor, but he is nonetheless more likely to regress than progress in 2020.

Sheffield's 2019 was a strange year. He struggled mightily while at Triple-A Tacoma, posting a 6.87 ERA in 12 starts and a relief appearance early in the year, but exploded for a 2.19 ERA in 12 starts following a demotion to Double-A Arkansas to ultimately earn a seven-start, big-league audition with the Mariners. While there, Sheffield's control wavered, continuing to have the look of a capable strikeout artist with a good ground-ball rate yet one who is wildly inconsistent. He'd have to open eyes during Cactus League play to warrant more than a late-round dart throw, and an AL-only one most likely at that.

There was some hype for Kelly's return stateside after four seasons in Korea, as some envisioned a Miles Mikolas-esque transition back to MLB. It ended up being a successful season for Kelly all things considered, as he threw 183.1 innings, the 12th most in the NL, and was worth two wins above replacement by FanGraphs' WAR. He had some homer issues but did not exacerbate those problems with walks (7.3 BB%). Kelly was not as valuable in the rotisserie game, as he was a detriment to the ratios, at least for the bulk of the year. He tapped into something extra over the final month and finished with a 2.18 ERA, .202 BAA and 35:11 K:BB in 33 September innings. Whether he can maintain those late improvements is the big question entering 2020, though his role is also somewhat in question with offseason addition Madison Bumgarner locked into a rotation spot.

One of the first two closers off the board in most fantasy drafts last spring, Treinen battled elbow, shoulder and back issues, lost the closer job and was ultimately non-tendered by the A's. After signing a one-year deal with the Dodgers, Treinen will look to recuperate some value before hitting the open market again next winter. His velocity held steady, but Treinen's command and control were way off -- likely due in part to the injuries -- with his Zone% falling more than six percentage points to 37.8%. That was one of the 20 worst marks among 158 qualified relievers. He was adamant after signing that he's "not a broken pitcher" and that 2019 was an outlier. Most will want to see it on the field first before investing, though if you grab Kenley Jansen, Treinen makes for a logical pick as a handcuff in the reserve rounds.

Since joining the Astros in 2015, Harris has quietly been one of the best relievers in the game, recording a 2.36 ERA and a 0.99 WHIP in that five-year span. A free agent after the 2019 season, Harris signed with the Nationals where he'll join the defending World Series champions as a setup man. Harris' strikeout and walk rates remain consistent and solid, though his hard-hit rate inched up last year. He throws a cutter and curve, with increasingly more use of the bender in each of the past two campaigns. Harris sits behind both Sean Doolittle and Daniel Hudson in the saves hierarchy, but since neither of his teammates are the bastion of health, Harris could get some ninth-inning duty at some point in the 2020 season.

Peacock's 29.4% strikeout rate the past three seasons combined is tantalizing if you're hoping he'll emerge a member of the Astros' rotation, but durability questions have seemingly destined him for a future in their bullpen. In shorter stints, his low-to-mid-90s fastball and slider can make him an innings-gobbling, ERA/WHIP/K's helper even in mixed leagues, but as a rotation member they leave him more susceptible to the matchups, best illustrated by his 86 point career wOBA split. Peacock is a strong AL-only late round pick, but his ceiling probably isn't as high as you perceive it.

Baseball's No. 1 pitching prospect entering 2019, Whitley endured an extremely disappointing campaign, marred by a shoulder issue coupled with shaky control (15.8% walk rate) that led to a 7.99 ERA in his 15 combined minor league starts and three relief appearances. He reported to Astros spring training healthy and with an adjustment to his mechanics, making him a name to watch as spring training unfolds. Whitley is almost assuredly going to begin 2020 in the minors, but with a strong start he could earn an early promotion and be an immediate-impact fantasy starter once he receives it.

Eflin performed capably as a No. 5 major-league starter last season, posting a 4.13 ERA over 32 appearances (28 starts). The ERA estimators are less kind to him on account of his low 18.3 K% and high 1.54 HR/9. Eflin does a good job against right-handed hitters but continues to have problems with lefties; he has allowed a .366 wOBA to lefty batters in his career, and that number sat at .356 in 2019. Of the 28 homers he served up last season, 17 were to lefties. He has good sinking movement on his fastball, but at this point it seems he may never develop a pitch to neutralize southpaw sluggers. Philadelphia has not made any major additions to its rotation, so Eflin projects to open the season in the rotation. Until further notice, Eflin is only a streaming option. He could be a weapon if used out of the bullpen.

Davies is something of an enigma. Once a fairly prolific groundballer, he became more of a flyball pitcher in 2019. The soft-tossing righty was lucky that the change, combined with the juiced ball, did not lead to a spike in homers; Statcast says Davies overachieved in the SLG department by more than 50 points and FIP says he overperformed his ERA by a full run. The other popular ERA estimators, namely xFIP and SIERA, are even harsher on Davies, saying he deserved an ERA north of 5.00. He managed just a 15.2 K% and had the second-lowest Zone% among regular starters last season (min. 150 IP). It wasn't the first time Davies outpitched his peripherals, having also done it by a significant margin in his 17-win 2017 season, but it's tough to bank on that trend continuing. Following an offseason trade to the Padres, Davies sees a park upgrade but likely loses some run support.

The No. 1 pick in the 2018 amateur draft, Mize kicked off 2019 with a 0.92 ERA and 26.4% strikeout rate in 13 starts combined between Class A Lakeland and Double-A Erie, before shoulder issues detailed what might've ultimately been the start of his big-league career. His ERA swelled to 7.09 in his final six outings for Erie, a sure sign that he'll begin 2020 in the minors, proving his full health as well as continued dominance of the minors' upper levels before earning that promotion. There's better-than-even odds that Mize will reach Detroit this summer, but he's more of a keeper- and dynasty-league prospect than a redraft stash as spring training dawned.

May entered 2019 a legitimate candidate to close for the Twins, who went with a committee from which Taylor Rogers ultimately emerged, and while he began in high-leverage, middle-relief spots, he again elevated his game to a closer-capable hurler during the second half. Check out these stats after the All-Star break: 2.81 ERA, .159 batting average allowed, 35.0% strikeout rate. While May's fly-ball leaning will probably keep his ERA from ever leading the relief pool, he has the skills you want from a top holds/ratios option.

Miley signed a one-year deal with the Astros last offseason, making it six teams in his past six seasons for the journeyman southpaw. On Sept. 1, he was 13-4, riding a seven-game winning streak with a nifty 3.06 ERA and 1.22 WHIP. In his final five starts, Miley posted an unsightly 16.68 ERA and 3.09 WHIP with seven walks to just six strikeouts in only 11.1 innings. The September swoon cost Miley a spot on the playoff roster. After signing with the Reds, it will be seven organizations in as many seasons for the nine-year veteran. The return to the Senior Circuit also comes with a reunion with pitching coach Derek Johnson. The two were together in Milwaukee, where Miley posted his best season, albeit in only 80.2 innings. Now 33 years old with mediocre stuff, Miley is best suited for NL-only formats with bench spots.

Lyles bounced around the league the past three seasons, spending time with the Rockies, Padres, Pirates and Brewers. For the second straight campaign, Milwaukee picked him up as a midseason acquisition in 2019, and there he found his groove, registering a 2.45 ERA and collecting seven wins over 11 starts. That led Texas to sign him to a two-year, $16 million contract in the offseason, but there are reasons to be wary of the success he found late last season. For one, his xFIP was 4.91, nearly double his stellar ERA. In addition, he was helped by an unsustainable .225 BABIP and 87.8 LOB%. Finally, Lyles' past performances leave much to be desired, as he owns a career 5.11 ERA (4.52 FIP) over more than 900 innings. Perhaps a rearrangement of his arsenal and increasingly better strikeout rates have revived his career, but it makes sense to tread lightly.

It's tempting to write Arrieta off entering his age-34 season, but keep in mind that he pitched with a bone spur in his elbow last year. While that did not dramatically affect his velocity, there's some thought that his release point was off and his extension was limited. Obviously it's impossible to quantify the impact the injury had on his numbers. After Arrieta had the spur removed, he will be looking to get back to the form we saw in 2017 and 2018. Arrieta was far from being the ace he used to be, but he was still an above-average major-league starter in 2017 and 2018, capable of providing wins and decent ratios on a good team. The strikeouts probably aren't coming back (18.5 K% last year) and you'll want to pick your spots early on, but you could do worse in the endgame.

Gonsolin enjoyed a successful rookie campaign in 2019, especially in light of his having been promoted into the Dodgers' parade of swingmen. He had as good an ERA as a starter (2.89) as in relief (3.00), but couldn't miss nearly as many bats in the former role (20.9% K rate, compared to 27.1% in relief). Gonsolin should be in the race for a roster spot this spring, but might have to settle for long-relief/swingman work yet again. He has intriguing skills, but is probably more of a scoop-him-up type only when moved into the rotation.

Even considering the uncertainty of a pitcher coming over from Japan, Kikuchi's first season in MLB was a major disappointment. His first 11 starts went swimmingly, as he recorded a 3.43 ERA and 1.08 WHIP over initial 60.1 innings. Things went downhill from there, though as Kikuchi registered a devilish 6.66 ERA and 1.78 WHIP the rest of the way. After allowing a reasonable eight homers in his first 11 games, Kikuchi surrendered a whopping 28 long balls over his final 101.1 frames. Known in Japan for his velocity, Kikuchi averaged a so-so 92.5 mph on his fastball, with only 15th-percentile spin. He also throws a slider, curve and changeup, with only the changeup (barely) rating as a plus-pitch. Kikuchi has the reputation of being a heady pitcher, so perhaps he can adjust. Heading into the season, though, he caps out as a streaming option in fantasy leagues.

A heavy-sinker, 70%-ground-ball reliever, Bummer's skill set elevates his ERA/WHIP floor due to his minimizing home runs while falling shy of a high Player Rater rating due to his so-so strikeout total in the age of the swing-and-miss. He had 27 holds last season as Alex Colome's primary setup man, and should be the White Sox's go-to left-hander in the seventh and eighth innings again in 2020. Bummer lacks a closer's ceiling, though, so expect a repeat of the holds and consider anything else gravy.

The perennial potential closer has not had a double-digit save year since 2016, but he keeps trucking along. The lanky lefty continues slinging the slider home at increasing rates, and it is now his primary pitch. His fastball velocity has lost a few ticks over the past few seasons, but the slider is still a strong pitch for him and the source of most of his strikeouts. His 30% strikeout rate looks closer-worthy, but on a contending team, his WHIP and home run rates simply will not play in the ninth inning. Carlos Martinez wants to become a starter, but Giovanny Gallegos has the better skills to take over the closer role. Draft Miller for strikeouts, vultured wins and spot saves and you will not be disappointed.

Lorenzen had a beneath-the-radar breakthrough in 2019, his first as a two-way player. This included six starts in center field and 29 total appearances in the outfield. Thanks to a tweak to his pitch selection and the return of his 97-mph average fastball velocity, he struck out a career-best 24.8% of the batters he faced, putting himself directly in the late-inning mix behind closer Raisel Iglesias. Lorenzen should occupy a similar role entering 2020, piling up the holds, with plenty of K's and solid ratios. He'll also grant you extra pop in daily leagues if you monitor the Reds lineup for his sporadic OF starts.

Gonzalez fell short of 150 innings for the first time in a decade, finishing with just 87.1 frames in 2019. He did not break camp with the Yankees and chose to opt out of his minor-league contract in late April, ultimately landing back with Milwaukee. While the lefty spent time on the injured list with arm issues, he fared reasonably well when on the field, continuing his strong run after first joining the Brewers 2018. His strikeout rate ticked back up and Gonzalez kept his home-run rate right around 0.9 HR/9, which is an especially strong mark considering the run environment and the home park he pitched in. The White Sox saw enough to commit $5 million to the veteran. He probably won't be afforded a long leash if he struggles, and the injury concerns aren't going away at his age, but Gonzalez looks like a viable streamer pitching in a bad division.

The majors' most common �opener� in 2018-19, drawing 56 such assignments before his 2019 deadline trade to the Marlins, Stanek saw his control collapse after his August return from a hip injury. While that might have explained his 19.2% walk rate for his new team, anything in double digits represents a poor mix for a pitcher with a 48% career fly-ball rate. Stanek can miss bats, but he'd be a shaky bet to close, especially with Brandon Kintzler now on the roster. Consider Stanek an NL-only pick or one who could help with holds, but only if it's throwing more effectively first during spring training.

A move to the bullpen last season unlocked Stephenson's full potential, as he went nearly 60% reliant upon his dominant slider while adding nearly 2 full mph to his fastball, pushing his strikeout rate to a professional-best 30.9%. In the process, he completed the year with nine holds, a 1.38 ERA and 0.73 WHIP in his final 24 appearances, giving himself a legitimate chance at entering 2020 as Raisel Iglesias' primary setup man. Stephenson's skill set is now on par with that of the game's better closers, making him one of the more intriguing speculative saves picks come draft day, but he's plenty capable of helping you in holds, ERA, WHIP and K's even if he remains in setup relief.

McHugh had a trio of nine-strikeout games early on, but his return to the starting rotation was short lived. He gave up 24 runs over a span of four starts from late April to early May and was moved to the bullpen. A lack of fastball command was pointed to initially as the reason for his removal from the rotation, but McHugh hit the IL with elbow soreness shortly thereafter. He also ended the year on the injured list with elbow issues, so it's fair to wonder if his arm ever felt fully right in 2019. The Astros gave up hope for a postseason return and formally shut McHugh down Sept. 17 with "continued pain" in the elbow. McHugh signed with the Red Sox during the offseason, and he'll compete for a rotation spot during spring training.

Diaz's long road back from Tommy John surgery began to show signs of promise late in 2019, as he had a 3.42 ERA, 1.18 WHIP and 27.5% strikeout rate in 23 appearances in the season's final two months, including a 5-for-6 performance as the Rockies' closer in September. With that role somewhat wide open entering 2020, Diaz could factor into the late-inning mix, armed with a high-90s fastball, sinker and slider that all performed well in 2019. Coors Field will limit the extent of his help in the ratio departments, but he should provide holds at the least and could be a top-20 closer if everything clicks.

Buttrey, a sleeper to close for the 2019 Angels, instead settled for a high-leverage setup role behind unexpected success story Hansel Robles, his 26 holds tied for 10th-most in the majors. It turned out to be the right move: Buttrey's 41% Statcast hard-contact rate ranked in the bottom 20% among pitchers, something he'll need to correct if he's to take the next step as a possible finisher. He's a handy source of holds and strikeouts, and an AL-only saves stash, but set your expectations at that while not assuming more.

Greene was a pleasant surprise during the first half of the 2019 campaign, notching 22 saves and posting a sparkling 1.09 ERA for the hapless Tigers. Weeks after tossing a scoreless inning in the All-Star Game, the right-hander was moved to Atlanta, where he was expected to take over as the team's closer. Things didn't go as planned, however, as Greene was relieved of ninth-inning duties after blowing two saves and giving up five earned runs in his first five appearances with the Braves. Though he eventually settled down, Greene never reclaimed the closing role. There are things to like about the 31-year-old -- among them, a career-best 6.7 BB% last season -- but his below-average fastball and middling 11.5% swinging-strike rate don't fit the profile of a shutdown closer. On a strong Atlanta team, he could at least be a good source of holds.

Considered one of the top pitching prospects in the game just a few years ago, Reyes lost the better part of three seasons to injury. First it was Tommy John surgery, performed in February of 2017. He made it back to St. Louis in the summer of 2018 but made just a single appearance before going down with a torn lat tendon, which also required surgery. Last season, a broken pinkie finger and a strained pectoral muscle conspired to limit Reyes to 40.1 total innings. The lack of durability has forced him into a relief role for 2020 and likely beyond. He has the stuff to be a major weapon in the bullpen and could eventually close, but this year will be mostly about proving he can stay on the field and contribute to the big-league squad.

Transitioning to the bullpen agreed with Newcomb. He began 2019 as a starter, but after walking eight with only five punch-outs in his first three outings, spanning just 12.1 frames, he was sent to Triple-A Gwinnett. He returned a few weeks later and proceeded to post a 2.89 ERA and 1.20 WHIP out of the bullpen, fanning 60 in 56 stanzas. As a reliever, Newcomb's fastball gained a tick, while he continued to generate grounders at a 50% clip. He'll reportedly be afforded the opportunity to compete for a return to the Braves' rotation with the fallback of returning to the bullpen, where he would be useful for fantasy in holds leagues after posting 16 of them last year.

Three years after undergoing Tommy John surgery, Gonzales filled the role of an innings-eater last season, throwing 203 frames to rank 12th in the league. The volume was critical for a shaky Seattle staff, but the southpaw's overall performance was a mild disappointment, as he regressed in most areas in comparison to his 2018 campaign. While Gonzales' 3.99 ERA was nearly identical to the 4.00 mark he posted the prior season, both his xFIP (5.11) and SIERA (5.08) represented dramatic increases over 2018's 3.59/3.81 results. Not coincidentally, both his strikeout rate (17.0%) and swinging-strike rate (8.2%) headed in the wrong direction, and even his solid 6.5 BB% was his highest mark since his rookie campaign. Gonzales did post an impressive 16 wins for one of baseball's worst teams, but his fantasy appeal is limited by his lack of strikeouts and low ceiling.

Early on in 2019, Strahm continued to flash upside, going six innings with three or fewer earned runs allowed six times over his first 10 starts. The big lefty even had a 10-strikeout game at Yankee Stadium in May. Unfortunately, his season was derailed by a rib strain. Strahm was rocked in his first few starts back from the IL and subsequently moved to the bullpen. The Padres announced in February that Strahm will work as a reliever in camp, so it seems like the ship has sailed in regards to him being a starter at the major-league level. In the bullpen, Strahm has a 2.71 ERA and 27.9 K%, much better than the 5.06 ERA and 24.1 K% he has posted as a starter. Strahm should have a long shelf life as a reliever, but saves will be hard to come by anytime soon with the additions of Drew Pomeranz and Emilio Pagan behind Kirby Yates.

Kahnle could be the best reliever no one knows. Granted, his outstanding 2019 season came on the heels of an injury-riddled 2018 but, when healthy, Kahnle has exhibited elite strikeout skills (albeit with inconsistent control). The right-hander battled shoulder and biceps issues two years ago, resulting in a loss of velocity. Kahnle's fastball regained its zip, though he used it less last year, relying more on his change-up. The adjustment worked as he avoided the IL, appearing in a career-high 72 games. The Yankees bullpen is loaded, but that won't prevent Kahnle from again being one of the league leaders in holds after posting 27 last season, tied for eighth-most in the majors.

Keller is a great example of a pitcher who can serve in one role for a non-contending team, but would be doing something else on a better squad. He is all fastballs and sliders, so the approach makes him tough on righties, but more susceptible to opposing lefties, at the plate. For his career, left-handers have reached base 36% of the time against Keller while righties have done so 29% of the time. Keller outings generally follow a pattern of him pitching carefully to lefties and letting his stuff play up against righties. The approach leads to a poor WHIP and a reliance on batted-ball outcomes to bounce his way. Ideally, he would be a reliever who shuts down opposing right-handers, but as a starter in Kansas City he is only draftable in deep AL-Only leagues.

There was a narrative going around last offseason, suggesting Freeland's strong 2018 campaign was in part due to growing up in Colorado; hence, he was used to pitching at altitude. The implication was he'd be able to maintain his success, but once again, Coors Field flexed its muscles, claiming another victim, as Freeland more than doubled his 2018 ERA, posting a bloated 6.73 mark in 22 starts. Even a trip to Triple-A Albuquerque didn't help, as he posted an 8.80 ERA in six starts for the Isotopes. The Rockies will give Freeland another shot in the rotation, but he'll need to upgrade a fastball with 34th percentile velocity and curve with 17th percentile spin to miss more bats and elicit weaker contact.

Count Anderson among the many achieving some success as a Rockies starter only for it to be short-lived. Last season, things hit rock bottom, as he posted an unsightly 11.76 ERA and 2.13 ERA in five starts covering just 20.2 frames. Anderson was demoted to Triple-A Albuquerque but didn't take the mound for the Isotopes, as it was determined he needed season-ending knee surgery. Colorado let Anderson go in the off-season, and he was subsequently claimed by the Giants. San Francisco also released Anderson but brought him back as a free agent. The lefty won't be ready until at least May, but the extreme upgrade in venues puts Anderson on the watch list as well as a potential stash in leagues with a deep reserve or an IL spot.

Junis' Statcast page is littered in blue, indicating "poor" rankings among his peers in virtually every statistical category. Most of the contact against Junis was loud last season, or at least medium-hit; he induced soft contact just 12.5% of the time, the lowest rate among qualified starters. Still mostly a fastball/slider pitcher with low velocity, Junis has struggled against lefty batters without that viable third pitch to combat them, and home runs have been a problem against both righties and lefties, and not just last year in a juiced-ball season. He is still only 27 years old, but there is really nothing in the underlying profile to get excited about. Junis has cleared 175 innings in back-to-back seasons and that volume does have value in certain points formats. In rotisserie leagues, Junis' appeal is minimal.

Last spring, nobody sucked in more draft helium than Pivetta, but once the season started, he just plain ? pitched poorly. The promising underlying metrics from his 2018 failed to manifest, as his skills eroded across the board, sending Pivetta to Triple-A after allowing 17 runs in his first four starts, tossing just 18.1 innings. After posting an encouraging 3.07 ERA and 1.10 WHIP with 58 strikeouts in 41 frames for Lehigh, Pivetta returned to the majors but continued to struggle, eventually moving to the bullpen. Still just 27 years old and armed with a 95 mph fastball and a curve with 92nd percentile spin, there's time for something to click, just don't pay for it until it happens.

Lauer was a steady presence in the Padres' rotation last season, taking the ball on Opening Day and starting 28 more games after that. The results were unspectacular -- particularly after the All-Star break, when he posted a 5.09 ERA over his last 13 appearances -- but he still pitched well enough to be included in an offseason trade that landed him with the Brewers. Lauer does not have dominant stuff, but he got by mainly with a fastball/cutter mix last season and has three other pitches in his arsenal. He's going to have to do a better job keeping runners off bases to bring more to the table in fantasy leagues, but the Brewers have had a lot of success in recent years getting the most out of pitchers with a similar profile. Lauer will not start Opening Day for a second straight year, but he's a safe bet to break camp with a spot somewhere in the rotation.

Once one of the top Padres pitching prospects, Quantrill's inability to develop a strikeout pitch, as well as San Diego drafting and acquiring several more promising arms, has dimmed his shine. Quantrill made his major-league debut last season and was in the process of rekindling his spark, sporting a 3.32 ERA and a 1.09 WHIP in 81 1/3 innings, albeit with a light 70 punch-outs. Unfortunately, Quantrill was blasted in his final five efforts, posting a 12.05 ERA and a 2.08 WHIP. The combination of tough opponents and "hitting the rookie wall" dampened his final numbers, but Quantrill exhibited enough to be in the mix for the last rotation spot, competing with the newly acquired Zack Davies.

Duffy remains a capable fifth starter miscast as the staff ace on a bad Royals team. His 4.63 ERA since the start of 2018 is the 13th-worst mark among the 90 pitchers who have thrown at least 250 combined innings over the past two seasons. His 1.41 WHIP in that span ranks sixth worst among that group. The veteran lefty's strikeout rate has hovered right around 20% for three seasons now, and his xwOBA on contact has been above .390 in three of the past four seasons. He spent time on the injured list with a left hamstring strain and has missed extended time in pretty much every year of his career, exceeding 155 innings only once. Some deep-league owners will inevitably stream Duffy at great risk to their ratios. A trade to a better team could help, but it's not worth speculating on. Throw that dart elsewhere on draft day.

Injuries and failure to develop a true strikeout pitch have curtailed Wacha's development. After an injury-riddled 2019 campaign in which Wacha pitched poorly between injuries (55 walks with only 104 punchouts in 126.2 innings), the Cardinals decided to cut bait and not pursue Walker as he entered free agency. The Mets are willing to hope something clicks, signing Wacha to a one-year deal. There's no reason for you to follow suit, as there is little chance Wacha can pitch well and stay healthy.

Anderson came back to life in 2019 with more innings pitched (176) than he amassed over the previous three seasons (147) combined. He has come back as an extreme pitch-to-contact hurler who surprisingly pitched better on the road (3.22 ERA, 1.15 WHIP) than he did at home (4.67 ERA, 1.49 WHIP.) One would assume Anderson's style would have suited Oakland's cavernous territory perfectly, but it did not. Anderson was much more effective against lefties last season, holding them to a .221 BA and .588 OPS, but righties teed off to the tune of a .280 BA and a .780 OPS. Home/road splits aside, the move to Milwaukee is a curious one given how harsh Miller Park can be on pitchers who struggle with their stuff, and the expected stats paint an unfavorable future for Anderson. A move to the bullpen at some point feels all but certain.

Now 38, Wainwright will be back for at least one more summer in the sun after re-upping with St. Louis. He was pretty much the exact same guy we saw in 2018, but over 31 starts instead of the mere eight he was limited to while battling elbow issues in 2018. His groundball, home-run and K-BB rates hardly budged, and Wainwright's WHIP remained north of 1.40. Lefty batters were a problem last year, but Wainwright at least held his own when he had the platoon edge, limiting right-handed hitters to a .297 wOBA. A few years ago, Wainwright famously called into a fantasy radio show to argue his worth in rotisserie baseball, but we'd like to believe even he would see the argument for a mixed-league roster spot as a losing cause at this stage. He remains in the mix for favorable home starts but possesses little upside.

Brebbia posted new career-highs with 72 appearances and 72 2/3 innings. While he wasn't one of the Cardinals' primary set-up men, he chipped in with a dozen holds, also a personal best. Brebbia pitched more than one inning on 24 occasions, so he shouldn't be impacted by the new reliver usage rules. The 29-year old righthander is an extreme fly ball pitcher but has only surrendered 11 homers in 123 1/3 innings over the past two years. Working 67 1/3 innings in Busch Stadium has helped him keep the ball in the yard, but he's still due some regression. A career 27% strikeout rate renders Brebbia viable in formats where dominant relievers are useful.

Heading into the 2019 season, there were signs Williams' 2018 campaign was at least part mirage, as the ERA estimators pegged his 3.11 ERA to be more than a run higher. The two lucky elements last season were a .261 BABIP and an 8% home run-per-fly ball mark. Sure enough, both regressed and then some, though the 2019 funky ball didn't help. Williams' 17.8% strikeout clip puts him at the mercy of batted-ball fate. With pitching ratios already quite tenuous in the current landscape, hurlers of Williams' ilk are risky, though some of that can be mitigated by streaming him at home in pitcher-friendly PNC Park.

At the All-Star break, Gant had a 2.22 ERA, 0.92 WHIP and .172 BAA over 44.2 innings. He went on to post a 6.65 ERA, 2.03 WHIP and .298 BAA in the second half, and his K-BB rate fell to just 1.9% after the intermission. The right-hander still finished with an 11-1 record and just a 2.9% opponents' barrel rate, ranking in the top 2% of the league in that statistic. Gant added more than two ticks to his fastball and his changeup induced swinging strikes nearly a quarter of the time. It's clear that Gant can be a very good major-league reliever, but the 11 wins are not repeatable and he will need to find his way into saves to be worthwhile outside of deep leagues. The door is open with Carlos Martinez wanting to move back into the rotation, but Giovanny Gallegos and Andrew Miller are both in the mix as well.

Over the last two seasons, only two players earned more holds than Stammen: Adam Ottavino and Tony Watson. In 2019 Stammen racked up 31 holds, tying for the major-league lead in the category, while posting his third straight season with an ERA under 3.30. In leagues counting holds, Stammen remains very much in the mix after he returned to San Diego on a three-year, $12 million deal in the offseason. In standard-scoring leagues, Stammen looks best left for the waiver wire as potential save chances are now well out of reach. He just does not have the strikeout punch (21.5 K% last year) to be worthwhile if he is not seeing save chances. Stammen does a great job limiting walks, but he only averages 92-93 mph on his fastball and there are now two more electric arms ahead of him -- Drew Pomeranz and Emilio Pagan -- behind closer Kirby Yates.

The versatile Romo served as both a closer and a setup man between stints with Miami and Minnesota last season, notching 20 saves and 17 holds while posting a 3.68 FIP. The right-hander will be 37 on Opening Day, but he is less prone to hitting an age wall due to his reliance on soft stuff. Romo's fastball settled in the mid-80s last season, and his primary pitch -- a slider -- was among the slowest in the league with an average velocity of 77.4 mph. Fortunately, hitters have trouble hitting Romo's pitches hard. In 2019, opponents managed a meager 84.6 mph average exit velocity against him, 11th lowest in the league (minimum 50 plate appearances). That, along with Romo's ability to limit walks (6.8 BB%) and fool hitters with off-speed stuff (14.1% swinging-strike rate), inspires confidence that he can again be an effective late-inning option.

Norris is miscast as a starting pitcher, and Detroit realized that by moving him into an opener role during the 2019 season. As evidence, his ERA the first time through the lineup in 2019 was 2.84, the second time through it climbed to 4.41, and the third time through it blew up to 9.26. Norris allowed 15 of his 22 home runs the second and third time through a lineup last season, and his opponents' batting average jumped from .259 the first two times through to .323 when he was left out there too long. Even bad teams need pitchers to soak up innings to give the bullpen a break, which explains why Norris piled up 23.1 third-time-through innings that damaged his overall numbers. He would be rosterable in some formats if Detroit promised never to extend him.

A poor spring ticketed Plutko to open the season with Triple-A Columbus where he was immediately put on the 7-day IL with a forearm strain. After rehabbing, Plutko was summoned to the majors in mid-May, going on to start 20 games as the Indians suffered several injuries to their rotation. Plutko is a fly-ball pitcher with good control, but he's not dominant so he's even more susceptible to the long ball. In fact, he surrendered 22 round-trippers in just 109 1/3 frames. Plutko will compete with Aaron Civale and Zach Plesac for two rotation openings and will likely end up on the outside, looking in. Even if he captures a spot, low strikeouts and a high ERA driven by home runs isn't a fantasy friendly combination.

Scouts have a saying: ?You can't teach velocity.? This explains why the Marlins are hell bent on finding a role for Urena and his 86th percentile (95 mph) sinking fastball. Control and the inability to develop secondary pitches have curtailed his development. Last season, Urena posted a 4.58 ERA and 1.45 WHIP in 74.2 innings as a starter, fanning only 51. After missing time with a back injury, Urena spent September as a reliever, recording a 9.00 ERA and 1.70 WHIP, albeit with 11 punch-outs in 10 frames. Urena, the Marlins' Opening Day starter the past two seasons, is expected to be stretched out in the spring. He wouldn't be the first to have something click, but it's only worth paying to find out in deep formats where streaming pitchers is a tactic.

Little went right for Familia last season as the once-dominant closer posted the worst season of his career. His 23% strikeout rate was lower than usual but his bloated 15.3% walk rate and a high .346 BABIP resulted in an excess of base runners and, hence, runs. Even his pristine HR rate swelled to 1.05 HR/9 -- still low but more than double his career 0.50 mark. Familia's velocity dropped a tick to 96 mph, but it was the complete loss of command and control doing the damage. Even with the increased benefit of a dominant middle reliver in today's fantasy landscape, there are better options out there than relying on the hope that Familia regains some effectiveness.

Things have gone downhill since Godley's breakthrough campaign in 2017. Last season, it bottomed out as Godley was banished to the Diamondbacks' bullpen after posting a 6.67 ERA and 1.59 WHIP after five starts. After recording a 5.36 ERA and 1.33 WHIP as a reliever, Arizona cut bait. Godley was claimed by the Blue Jays, with whom he logged a 4.82 ERA and 1.55 WHIP before being waived and outrighted to Triple-A Buffalo to finish the season. Detroit signed Godley to a minor league deal. Rebuilding teams are a good landing spot for reclamation projects, your fantasy roster is not.

Vargas' 2019 season will probably be remembered for one thing: he threatened to beat up a Mets reporter. His performance on the field was forgettable, with the lefty posting a 7-9 record for the second straight year. Two of the top estimators, xFIP and SIERA, say Vargas should have had an ERA north of 5.00 on account of his middling strikeout (19.1%) and walk (9.7%) rates. He fell behind in the count more often and his chase rate dipped. After Vargas posted a 5.19 ERA in the second half, the Phillies -- who acquired Vargas from New York in a July trade -- declined his option, choosing to pay Vargas $2 million to get out of town rather than $8 million to pitch for the team in 2020. At age 37, Vargas can probably eat innings for a second-division team if he chooses to return for another season.

A suspension for violating MLB's domestic violence policy will sideline German for the first 63 games of the Yankees' season. Upon his eligible return, he should slide back into the rotation, where for 12 starts and a relief appearance to begin his 2019 he was on track for one of the season's biggest pitching breakthroughs, his ERA 3.86, WHIP 1.11 and strikeout rate 26.7% during that time. After a near-month-long IL stint for a hip injury, he wasn't quite as dominant, with 4.19/1.18/25.1% numbers that seem more realistic going forward. Despite his early absence, German is worth stashing in mixed leagues for the season's final four months, but be forewarned that you'll have to do so with him on your bench, which can be limiting in ESPN's three-bench-spots standard.

Once a reliable innings eater, Archer's durability has taken a hit, as injuries have held him under 150 frames each of the past two seasons. The decreasing volume is especially troubling, since his lone strength at this point in his career is the ability to accumulate strikeouts. The veteran ranked in the bottom 20% among pitchers who threw 100 or more innings last season across various categories, including FIP (5.02), walk rate (10.5%) and HR/FB (20.2%). The swing-and-miss stuff is still there -- Archer posted a strong 27.2 K% and 12.9% swinging-strike rate last season -- but that's not enough to balance an ERA that has increased each of the past four years, ballooning to 5.19 in 2019. The strikeout numbers are tantalizing, but given the injury concerns and overall downward trend of Archer's career, he's best viewed as a streaming option in mixed fantasy leagues.
Syndergaard underwent Tommy John surgery and will not play in 2020.
Munoz had Tommy John surgery in March and will not pitch for the Padres in 2020.

Injuries have sidetracked each of Sale's past two seasons as well as this one, as he made three trips to the injured list between the 2018 All-Star break alone and the end of 2019, totaling 85 lost days, then succumbed to season-ending Tommy John surgery in March.
Beede had Tommy John surgery and will miss the 2020 season.
Severino (Tommy John surgery) will not pitch in 2020 and is only a dynasty-league consideration in this year's drafts.

A glance at Price's final 2019 numbers makes it easy to forget that the southpaw held the second-best FIP (2.85) in the first half of the campaign among American League starters. A disastrous second half brought Price's FIP up to 3.62, though that was still a better mark than in his previous two seasons. It's reasonable to assume that the cyst in Price's left wrist that brought his campaign to a premature end played a part in his second-half struggles. He posted enough encouraging signs throughout the season -- including a career-best 27.9 K% and a typically solid 7.0 BB% -- to suggest that he still has plenty to offer on the mound. Health has been a question mark for Price in the late stages of his career, but with the cyst removed and a full offseason to rest, he could significantly outperform his ADP.

September 2018 Tommy John surgery cost Kopech the entirety of the 2019 season, but he was expected to report to spring training with no restrictions. Before the operation, he was one of the top pitching prospects in the game, capable of reaching 100 mph with his fastball while sporting solid breaking pitches, but he had some issues with control in the minors and had an extreme fly-ball leaning in a four-start audition with the big club in 2018. Kopech has never exceeded 140 2/3 innings in any season as a pro and therefore might be handled conservatively by the White Sox, but the shortened schedule alleviates many of those worries. He might quickly capture a big-league rotation spot and the high upside that'll come with it. Monitor him closely, stash him for now and regard him a great dynasty-league prospect.

Clase will serve an 80-game suspension for testing positive for Boldenone, effectively ending his 2020 before it started, though the league has announced the remaining 20 games of the penalty will not carry over into 2021.

With the emergence of Zac Gallen last season and the addition of Madison Bumgarner in free agency, it looks like there will be only two rotation spots available between Leake, Merrill Kelly and Luke Weaver. In terms of big-league experience, Leake is head and shoulders above the other two. On merit, Leake is arguably last among those three options. His groundball rate declined seven percentage points over the past two seasons, and the balls that got up did more damage in 2019, with Leake posting by far the worst home-run rate of his career (1.87 HR/9). He continues to rank among the best starters in walk rate (just a 3.2 BB% last year), but the strikeouts have never been there. If the home runs remain at last season's level, Leake won't be long for a starting role in the big leagues.
